															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tsercele" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2891035); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2891035&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610224941" alt="Tsercele" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2891035)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tsercele" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2891035); return false;" >Tsercele</a></span> <span class="odate time_1578597451 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">09 Jan 2020 19:17</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4464847">
									

<p>alexa they are so angry play track 6 forever</p>
<p>This installment is (obviously) inspired by John Mulaney's excellent &quot;<a href="https://www.vulture.com/2019/11/john-mulaney-salt-and-pepper-diner-joke.html">Salt and Pepper Diner</a>&quot; routine. As it turns out, the joke is not so fun for the captive audience &#8212; particularly when it's being used as pataphysical camouflage.</p>
<p>Thanks go out to <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zyn" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1404533); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1404533&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1578665306" alt="Zyn" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1404533)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zyn" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1404533); return false;">Zyn</a></span> for providing draft critique, and to <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kinchtheknifeblade" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1345012); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1345012&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1578665306" alt="kinchtheknifeblade" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1345012)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kinchtheknifeblade" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1345012); return false;">kinchtheknifeblade</a></span> for looking over this story pre-release! Much appreciated!</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Easter&nbsp;Eggs</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Easter&nbsp;Eggs</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<ul>
<li>&quot;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Incredible_Melting_Man" target="_blank">The Incredible Melting Man</a>&quot; (1977) was featured in Episode 704 of MST3K. (Wren isn't quite &quot;genre-savvy&quot; enough to realize that their choice of attire might foreshadow an <em>emotional</em> meltdown.)</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Gore's scheme reminds Masterson of John le Carré's &quot;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Spy_Who_Came_In_from_the_Cold" target="_blank">The Spy Who Came In from the Cold</a>&quot; (1963), which explores the relationship between personal motivation and amorality through a series of elaborate feints.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Masterson compares their &quot;tracking&quot; issues to Christopher Nolan's &quot;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Memento_(film)">Memento</a>&quot; (2000), which is a mystery/drama (presented mostly in reverse order) about an amnesiac who marks their experiences with photos and tattoos. This also dovetails with their circumvention of Foundation amnestics: <span class="dblock">they have a Handycam magically wired to their optic nerve. Just in case</span>.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Wren quotes Alan Moore and David Lloyd's &quot;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/V_for_Vendetta" target="_blank">V for Vendetta</a>&quot; (1982) on their way out the door. Partially because of the obvious anarchist influence, and partially because <span class="dblock">Anna Bojarski spent way too much time on 4chan before the exhibition in 2008</span>.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>&quot;23&quot; (2:30) continues to be <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/23_enigma" target="_blank">meaningless</a>. Probably. Mostly. Don't worry about it.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>

